<subSubSection id="0BB0657DFFC6FFFA50A7FB17A3607A62" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="431536F6FFC6FFFA50A7FB17A0587BD5" blockId="6.[189,310,1223,1249]" box="[189,310,1223,1249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<heading id="185D819AFFC6FFFA50A7FB17A0587BD5" bold="true" box="[189,310,1223,1249]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" reason="3">
<emphasis id="71DEEAE4FFC6FFFA50A7FB17A0587BD5" bold="true" box="[189,310,1223,1249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="431536F6FFC6FFFA50A7FB25A3607A62" blockId="6.[189,1399,1269,1366]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Small-sized 
<taxonomicName id="84AA4D75FFC6FFFA5155FB25A0D77A3B" authorityName="Winnertz" authorityYear="1867" box="[335,441,1269,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Sciaridae" genus="Bradysia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="71DEEAE4FFC6FFFA5155FB25A0D77A3B" box="[335,441,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Bradysia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Brown. Maxillary palpus with 3 segments, segment 1 with shallow sensory area. Wing length 
<quantity id="84529B13FFC6FFFA5149FAC9A08C7A07" box="[339,482,1305,1331]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="1.6" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.5">1.5–1.7 mm</quantity>
, veins indistinct. Gonostylus narrow, mesially impressed, with apical tooth and 5–6 megasetae in one group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0BB0657DFFC6FFFA50A7FAADA3A97ADD" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="431536F6FFC6FFFA50A7FAADA02A7AA3" blockId="6.[189,324,1405,1431]" box="[189,324,1405,1431]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<heading id="185D819AFFC6FFFA50A7FAADA02A7AA3" bold="true" box="[189,324,1405,1431]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" reason="3">
<emphasis id="71DEEAE4FFC6FFFA50A7FAADA02A7AA3" bold="true" box="[189,324,1405,1431]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="431536F6FFC6FFFA50A7FA7CA3A97ADD" blockId="6.[189,1399,1452,1513]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The name is derived from the Latin words 
<emphasis id="71DEEAE4FFC6FFFA52ACFA7CA38C7AF2" box="[694,738,1452,1478]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">falx</emphasis>
(scythe) and - 
<emphasis id="71DEEAE4FFC6FFFA5396FA7DA2AE7AF2" box="[908,960,1453,1478]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">ceps</emphasis>
(of the head), referring to the curved apical tooth of the gonostylus of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
